This is the first half of #13514 as a standalone PR.

There is a bug but my VS Code doesn't show any error. What's more, the Infoview is updated on every line as if it was a correct proof. How is it possible?

PS: "Restart file" doesn't help. Restarting VS Code doesn't help either.

I could reproduce locally the behavior you describe: No error shown. However, your version of mathlib was ancient in this PR, so I merged master and the error appeared. The lack of error locally was probably due to the new variable inclusion mechanism not being available yet on this branch, meaning that you were referring some far out `hn₀` (instead of receiving an error, since your hypothesis is called `hn`).

> I could reproduce locally the behavior you describe: No error shown. However, your version of mathlib was ancient in this PR, so I merged master and the error appeared. The lack of error locally was probably due to the new variable inclusion mechanism not being available yet on this branch, meaning that you were referring some far out `hn₀` (instead of receiving an error, since your hypothesis is called `hn`).

Thank you very much! I will give it a try now.
It seems the only remaining problem was that `List.filterMap` is no longer a `@[simp]` lemma.

What is wrong here, please?
```
invalid occurrence of universe level 'u_2' at 'ContextFreeGrammar.Embedding.GoodString', it does not occur at the declaration type, nor it is explicit universe level provided by the user, occurring at expression
  Good.{uT, u_2, u_1} a
at declaration body
  fun {T : Type uT} {g : ContextFreeGrammar T} (s : List (Symbol T g.NT)) ↦ ∀ ⦃a : Symbol T g.NT⦄, a ∈ s → Good a
```

It's hard to debug without opening the branch and I'm busy doing something else, but basically you should track that `u_2` universe down, starting from `Good`, by setting `set_option pp.universes true` and seeing where it appears
I have now read your paper with Jasmin. Here are a few comments in consequence
I have now read your paper with Jasmin. Here are a few comments in consequence

Why not
```suggestion
/-- Mapping `Symbol` when it is a nonterminal. -/
def Symbol.map {N₀ N T₀ T : Type*} (f : T₀ → T) (g : N₀ → N) : Symbol T₀ N₀ → Symbol T N
  | Symbol.terminal t => Symbol.terminal (f t)
  | Symbol.nonterminal n => Symbol.nonterminal (g n)
```
This matches `Sum.map`
Yes but it would introduce additional useless argument.
Are you sure you will never need to map the terminal symbols?

If it ever happens, I will use a different mapping function that changes terminals only. Throughout the whole file, terminals and nonterminals are treated in "asymmetric" ways. Note that one of them is a type argument and the other is a field of any given grammar.

```suggestion
/-- Map the type of nonterminal symbols of a `ContextFreeRule` . -/
```
and similar for other docstrings
Could the docstring speak less roughly?
I added something; feel free to write something different.

Using "terminal" and "nonterminal" in place of "terminal symbol" and "nonterminal symbol" is quite idiosyncratic and definitely hampers comprehension
```suggestion
that the resulting grammar preserves derivations of those strings that may contain any terminal symbols but
only the proper nonterminal symbols. The embedding operation must be injective. The projection operation
```
and below

Are you sure that you want to use "terminal symbols" and "nonterminal symbols" only?

In the ITP paper that documents the Lean 3 library, I was naming it as follows:
let `(n : g.NT)`
`n` .. nonterminal
`Symbol.nonterminal n` ... nonterminal symbol

```suggestion
/-- A pair of `ContextFreeGrammar`s with maps between their types of nonterminal symbols that work,
```

You shouldn't rely on the order of the fields in docstrings
```suggestion
  /-- The function on nonterminal symbols is injective. -/
```
Both are functions on nonterminal symbols. How do you want to distinguish them in the docstring?

```suggestion
  /-- The embedding map is injective. -/
```

I think this will be more useful to you
```suggestion
  project_inj ⦃x y⦄ : projectNT x ≠ none → projectNT x = projectNT y → x = y
```

Can you please eliminate the `∃`? In fact, why is the lemma not
```suggestion
lemma EmbeddedContextFreeGrammar.projectNT_inverse_embedNT (G : EmbeddedContextFreeGrammar T) {x n₀} :
    G.projectNT x = some n₀ → G.embedNT n₀ = x := by
```

```suggestion
  ∀ ⦃a⦄, a ∈ s → Good a
```
I don't understand nonterminal this sentence

```suggestion
/-- Production by `G.g₀` can be mirrored by production by `G.g`. -/
```
Same here

```suggestion
inductive EmbeddedContextFreeGrammar.Good : Symbol T G.g.NT → Prop
  | terminal (t : T) : Good (.terminal t)
  | nonterminal (n : G.g.NT) (n₀ : G.g₀.NT) (hn : G.projectNT n = n₀) : Good (.nonterminal n)
```
will probably be nicer to work with

```suggestion
/-- Mapping `Symbol` when it is a nonterminal symbol. -/
```
and below
Please reply to my overall comment about "nonterminal" vs "nonterminal symbol".

I think anonymous dot notation is really useful here to unclutter
```suggestion
  | .terminal t => .terminal t
  | .nonterminal n => .nonterminal (f n)
```
and below
This is still really uninformative. Please improve.
I don't know how to describe it in words without repeating the entire definition informally in the docstring.

```suggestion
/-- An embedding from a context-free grammar `g₀` to a context-free grammar `g` is an embedding
`embedNT` of the nonterminal symbols from the former to the latter along with a one-sided inverse
`projectNT` such that all rewrite rules of `g` that end in `embedNT n₀` for some `n₀` come from some
rule in `g₀`. -/```
Do you have a reference for this?
I have a reference for a similar structure.
https://arxiv.org/pdf/2302.06420 page 6

In your paper, the smaller and bigger grammars are pre-existing. This hints at your definition being over-bundled:
```suggestion
structure ContextFreeGrammar.Embedding {T : Type uT} (g₀ g : ContextFreeGrammar T) where
```
You don't need to assume this: `projectNT_embedNT` already implies it

I believe you don't need `project_inj` at all. Here's my reasoning:
1. All you care about is that `projectNT` is a one-sided inverse to `embedNT`.
2. This already implies that `projectNT` is injective on the range of `embedNT`.
3. Hence all `project_inj` is giving you is that `projectNT` is also injective outside of the range of `embedNT`.
4. But `projectNT`might as well always be `none` outside of the range of `embedNT` (you could even enforce that if you wanted).
5. Therefore you don't need `project_inj`.

pullRequest.title: feat(Computability/ContextFreeGrammar): mapping between two types of nonterminal symbols
